Brenda's Soul Food is truly a gem in San Francisco. The only caveat being its long wait to be seated. That being said, you can circumvent this problem by coming during off hours (late lunch at 2:30-3pm or early dinner at 5pm), when the wait is just 15-20 minutes or so. I can pretty confidently say this is one of my favorite places for Southern Food in the Bay Area. Their beignets are definitely the best I have had in the area. Of course, it is nowhere along the lines of Ca Du Monde in New Orleans. If this is your first time here, I'd recommend opting for the Beignet sampler, especially if you're coming with a party of 3 or more. However, it is a bit too much for a party 2, that is if you're planning to order other things to eat (which I highly recommend). TIP: eat the crawfish beignet FIRST, before the cheesy crawfish filling gets cold---then it's just solidified cheese. The other sweet beignets can wait. My favorite flavor so far has been the Ghirardelli dark chocolate beignet. I found the apple one to be a bit too tart, and dense. The plain beignet was alright, Angeline's Louisiana Kitchen does a better plain beignet, imo. Now onto the other dishes! I LOVE gumbo and shrimp & grits. And I have the say, the gumbo is DEFINITELY a MUST. I would say, after the beignet, the next sure thing to order is the gumbo. It had the perfect texture with lots of okra and sausages. The rice to stew ratio was also perfect. Shrimp & Grits can be hit or miss for some of you, depending on your taste palate. I am used to more savory shrimp & grits, so Brenda's were a bit too sweet for me. However, it is your most famous dish. My husband enjoyed it a lot as a well. Other than the sweetness, I thought the texture of the grits were made really well! They also pack it with a of shrimp gravy on top. It tastes great with pretty much anything. We loved topping it on top of the biscuits *carbs on carbs mmmMMmm* The only disappointment was the Fried Chicken. I had VERY high hopes for the fried chicken. And to be honest, it was a pretty big disappointment. Dry, greasy/non-flaking skin, and tough meat. I also though the cut of chicken used was also not that great. Definitely no bueno. I would discourage ordering this in the future. That said, if you DO LOVE a good fried chicken, head over to Farmer Brown's Little Skillet in SOMA. They make a really good one. But yes, don't try it here. Other than that, there were many delicious dishes that we enjoyed at Brenda's. Just don't touch the chicken, and you're solid! Great for sharing among big parties because the portions are very generous. Prices are also lower than most restaurants in SF. It's in a slightly sketchier neighborhood in the Tenderloin, so bring your friends!

The service, food, decor, and atmosphere were all stellar!!

Brenda's gets a lot of hype, so the lines can generally range from 20 minutes to an hour. I went during non peak hours and only waited ~20. It's a small space but the table felt considerably spacious and made for a comfortable stay. I loved the mac & cheese (though it was a LITTLE heavier than my liking), and the biscuit was to die for. The beignets tasted okay in my opinion but I wasn't a fan if the red spice on top, though I'm glad I tried it because it's one of their most popular items. Overall, it's a staple SF restaurant and it's worth going once.

I enjoyed the Grillade & Grits. It sounds fancy, but it tastes like an elevated can of chili and scrambled eggs, which I enjoyed. It's simple, comforting and satisfying. It's not spicy and is super filling (can feed two) with plenty of toast for dipping. I think this might be familiar to children who are picky eaters. The plain beignets, however, are not worth it. The white "meat" of the beignet is so darn dense and tough, it's like biting into a bolillo or hoagie bread roll lightly dusted with powdered sugar. I'll never get these again. I'm hoping Brenda's uses a fluffier batter for the plain beignets in the future.

Everyone I know rants and raves about this spot, and as much as I hate waiting (versus making a reservation), I finally made it out here for brunch (twice in one week actually). I recommend getting there before you are actually hungry/starving because you'll be waiting. You write your name on a chalkboard, and that's how the line works. Note: there's no sun outside because of the buildings, so wear a jacket. I got to try a few things: we got the crawfish beignets -- which FYI you get three HUGE beignets. Honestly, I can't get this and an entree it's too much for me -- but I took them home. These are really good - crawfish and cheesy, definitely worth trying. I also tried the shrimp & grits -- this was super delicious and it comes with a LOT of cheesy grits (I couldn't finish this either). The fried chicken benedict was super delicious -- the fried chicken was bomb and it's served on biscuit instead of an english muffin - so good. I would definitely recommend this spot and will return because it's a different kind of brunch -- instead of the same old stuff.

I've had horrible grits my whole life and today, Brenda's has changed my life for the better. I've never consumed something so fast, the cheesy, smooth, textured, melting grits along with the perfectly cooked pork belly has made me complete. 10/10 would come again

I first had Brenda's years ago. At the time, the roommate worked in the area, so I asked him to bring us take out home for dinner. I remember enjoying everything we ordered. Especially the crawfish beignet, fried chicken and mac and cheese. Last Thursday, July 30th a little before 6pm, I decided to try Brenda's again. We ordered through Caviar and our dinner arrived a little before 7pm. Prices below are what I paid using Caviar. *Crawfish beignet ($3.57): spiced with cayenne, scallions & cheddar I loved the filling, but the beignets were a little too doughy and slightly bitter. Too much cayenne? These are also super oily. *Sweet flight of beignet ($6): 3 per order - plain, chocolate and granny smith I don't know why, but I didn't enjoyed their beignets as much. My favorite was the plain one since it was fluffy with a nice chew. The apple filling was a little dry and the chocolate filling a little too thick. *Chicken, sausage & okra gumbo ($5.10 cup) I didn't try this as I don't like gumbo, but the roommate finished the whole thing. *BFC dinner ($17.09): three pieces of Brenda's secret recipe fried chicken, their famous cream biscuit, hot pepper jelly & collard greens I remember this being so much better! The breading was crunchy with good flavor, but the chicken pieces were super small. It didn't seem worth the price. Not much meat on the bones. *Oyster flight ($8.42): Casino - bacon, scallion, biscuit, crumbs, parmesan, gruyere; Tchoupitoulas - cayenne butter, garlic, herbs; Orleans - Blackened voodoo bbq sauce I love oysters, so I enjoyed this. Casino was probably my fav, then Tchoupitoulas and lastly Orleans. *Bbq pork and ribs ($16.07): mac & cheese, collard greens Yum! The ribs were tender and meaty. The only disappointing thing was they forgot to pack our mac & cheese. And I love mac & cheese. That was actually really sad. *Shrimp & grits ($13.75): sauteed shrimp, cheddar grits, spicy tomato-bacon gravy So I don't normally eat grits, but I've been craving a lot of carbs lately. The grits were fluffy and the shrimp tender. And the ooey gooey cheese just brought it all together. Super tasty. Some really solid dishes and some not. I really wish I got to try the mac & cheese again and the fried chicken was as good as I remember. Maybe one day, I'll actually eat at Brenda's. But until then, 3 stars.

The building is pretty narrow and feels like a hole in a wall kinda place. Lots of hearty dishes on the menu. I tried the hush puppies (great tasting but a little on the greasy side) and the beignet flight (I really only wanted dessert). I'm not much of a soul food or even country food eater, so I don't know that I would return for the food, but I can appreciate the quality and the ambiance that they put into this place.

    Brenda's Soul Food is truly a gem in San Francisco. The only caveat being its long wait to be seated. That being said, you can circumvent this problem by coming during off hours (late lunch at 2:30-3pm or early dinner at 5pm), when the wait is just 15-20 minutes or so.

    I can pretty confidently say this is one of my favorite places for Southern Food in the Bay Area. Their beignets are definitely the best I have had in the area. Of course, it is nowhere along the lines of Ca Du Monde in New Orleans. If this is your first time here, I'd recommend opting for the Beignet sampler, especially if you're coming with a party of 3 or more. However, it is a bit too much for a party 2, that is if you're planning to order other things to eat (which I highly recommend). TIP: eat the crawfish beignet FIRST, before the cheesy crawfish filling gets cold---then it's just solidified cheese. The other sweet beignets can wait. My favorite flavor so far has been the Ghirardelli dark chocolate beignet. I found the apple one to be a bit too tart, and dense. The plain beignet was alright, Angeline's Louisiana Kitchen does a better plain beignet, imo.

    Now onto the other dishes! I LOVE gumbo and shrimp & grits. And I have the say, the gumbo is DEFINITELY a MUST. I would say, after the beignet, the next sure thing to order is the gumbo. It had the perfect texture with lots of okra and sausages. The rice to stew ratio was also perfect. Shrimp & Grits can be hit or miss for some of you, depending on your taste palate. I am used to more savory shrimp & grits, so Brenda's were a bit too sweet for me. However, it is your most famous dish. My husband enjoyed it a lot as a well. Other than the sweetness, I thought the texture of the grits were made really well! They also pack it with a of shrimp gravy on top. It tastes great with pretty much anything. We loved topping it on top of the biscuits *carbs on carbs mmmMMmm*

    The only disappointment was the Fried Chicken. I had VERY high hopes for the fried chicken. And to be honest, it was a pretty big disappointment. Dry, greasy/non-flaking skin, and tough meat. I also though the cut of chicken used was also not that great. Definitely no bueno. I would discourage ordering this in the future. That said, if you DO LOVE a good fried chicken, head over to Farmer Brown's Little Skillet in SOMA. They make a really good one. But yes, don't try it here.

    Other than that, there were many delicious dishes that we enjoyed at Brenda's. Just don't touch the chicken, and you're solid! Great for sharing among big parties because the portions are very generous. Prices are also lower than most restaurants in SF. It's in a slightly sketchier neighborhood in the Tenderloin, so bring your friends!

    Everyone I know rants and raves about this spot, and as much as I hate waiting (versus making a reservation), I finally made it out here for brunch (twice in one week actually).  

    I recommend getting there before you are actually hungry/starving because you'll be waiting.  You write your name on a chalkboard, and that's how the line works.  Note: there's no sun outside because of the buildings, so wear a jacket.  

    I got to try a few things: we got the crawfish beignets -- which FYI you get three HUGE beignets.  Honestly, I can't get this and an entree it's too much for me -- but I took them home.  These are really good - crawfish and cheesy, definitely worth trying.  I also tried the shrimp & grits -- this was super delicious and it comes with a LOT of cheesy grits (I couldn't finish this either).  The fried chicken benedict was super delicious -- the fried chicken was bomb and it's served on biscuit instead of an english muffin - so good.

    I would definitely recommend this spot and will return because it's a different kind of brunch -- instead of the same old stuff.

    1 check-in

    I first had Brenda's years ago. At the time, the roommate worked in the area, so I asked him to bring us take out home for dinner. I remember enjoying everything we ordered. Especially the crawfish beignet, fried chicken and mac and cheese.

    Last Thursday, July 30th a little before 6pm, I decided to try Brenda's again. We ordered through Caviar and our dinner arrived a little before 7pm. Prices below are what I paid using Caviar.

    *Crawfish beignet ($3.57): spiced with cayenne, scallions & cheddar
    I loved the filling, but the beignets were a little too doughy and slightly bitter. Too much cayenne? These are also super oily.

    *Sweet flight of beignet ($6): 3 per order - plain, chocolate and granny smith
    I don't know why, but I didn't enjoyed their beignets as much. My favorite was the plain one since it was fluffy with a nice chew. The apple filling was a little dry and the chocolate filling a little too thick.

    *Chicken, sausage & okra gumbo ($5.10 cup)
    I didn't try this as I don't like gumbo, but the roommate finished the whole thing.

    *BFC dinner ($17.09): three pieces of Brenda's secret recipe fried chicken, their famous cream biscuit, hot pepper jelly & collard greens
    I remember this being so much better! The breading was crunchy with good flavor, but the chicken pieces were super small. It didn't seem worth the price. Not much meat on the bones.

    *Oyster flight ($8.42): Casino - bacon, scallion, biscuit, crumbs, parmesan, gruyere; Tchoupitoulas - cayenne butter, garlic, herbs; Orleans - Blackened voodoo bbq sauce
    I love oysters, so I enjoyed this. Casino was probably my fav, then Tchoupitoulas and lastly Orleans.

    *Bbq pork and ribs ($16.07): mac & cheese, collard greens
    Yum! The ribs were tender and meaty. The only disappointing thing was they forgot to pack our mac & cheese. And I love mac & cheese. That was actually really sad.

    *Shrimp & grits ($13.75): sauteed shrimp, cheddar grits, spicy tomato-bacon gravy
    So I don't normally eat grits, but I've been craving a lot of carbs lately. The grits were fluffy and the shrimp tender. And the ooey gooey cheese just brought it all together. Super tasty.

    Some really solid dishes and some not. I really wish I got to try the mac & cheese again and the fried chicken was as good as I remember. Maybe one day, I'll actually eat at Brenda's. But until then, 3 stars.

    Really great vibe at this joint; feels old time and screams southern.

    The wait was pretty long during dinner time, definitely a lot of people wanting to eat here, but not a ton of seats. The building is pretty narrow and feels like a hole in a wall kinda place.

    Lots of hearty dishes on the menu. I tried the hush puppies (great tasting but a little on the greasy side) and the beignet flight (I really only wanted dessert).

    I'm not much of a soul food or even country food eater, so I don't know that I would return for the food, but I can appreciate the quality and the ambiance that they put into this place.
